n works if there isn’t cached dependency. Maybe the TCK is isolated and needs downloading. But it's strange that I’m seeing \\\\\\\"Could not resolve\\\\\\\" issues. It seems any test involving XmlPath is failing due to a missing dependency. I'm unsure why tests are needed for xml-path. Should I inspect whether there’s a group artifact in /tmp? If Gradle doesn’t show unresolved dependencies, I must check how to set up tests without compile-time dependencies on XmlPath.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Analyzing compile errors**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering possible causes for the compile errors. It doesn't seem related to the filename being uppercase. The `public class` instruction should generally work fine in Groovy, but maybe I can't have multiple public classes in one file. I'm also wondering if the compileTestGroovy fails due to existing files conflicting with `Xml_pathTest.groovy`. There might be a limitation with the native image test generator and how TCK handles multiple files. If existing tests remain unchanged, can I add new test classes without issues? I need to explore ways to resolve this.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test modifications**\\\\n\\\\nI'm exploring how to get the tests to pass. One idea is to replace the current test with a \\\\\\\"plain\\\\\\\" JUnit test that has no external imports, but I still need to ensure I cover the uncovered feature. If compiling issues stem from the XmlPath import, that complicates things. Could I also try using fully qualified names for imports? What about removing the test file altogether? The user insists on maintaining tests, so maybe I should update existing placeholders instead, while adhering to their request for unchanged tests. I'm still unsure how harness limitations might impact this.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Investigating compile issues**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking there might be a compile failure happening due to the Native image plugin needing the test class name to be exactly `${artifact-id with underscores}Test`. Maybe there are additional tests that weren't included? While the overall compile is fine, I should look into the settings and see if Gradle convention is scanning only one class. Let’s inspect that further!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_ykdi5rXyFi8a9cbOhL9IFt11|fc_02855ba501e27c0b0169ff592ba4f881a387fbaf3abf3f5a7a\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"find tests/src/io.rest-assured/xml-path/5.5.0 -maxdepth 3 -type f -name '*.gradle' -o -name 'settings.gradle' -o -name 'gradle.properties' -print\", \"timeout\": 10}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 288, \"output\": 636, \"cacheRead\": 60416, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 61340, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1778342173009, \"responseId\": \"resp_02855ba501e27c0b0169ff591db8b081a3bd952163dab666a1\"}}\n24692:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Debugging dependency issues**\\n\\nI'm trying to understand how the compilation works if there isn’t cached dependency. Maybe the TCK is isolated and needs downloading. But it's strange that I’m seeing \\\"Could not resolve\\\" issues. It seems any test involving XmlPath is failing due to a missing dependency. I'm unsure why tests are needed for xml-path. Should I inspect whether there’s a group artifact in /tmp? If Gradle doesn’t show unresolved dependencies, I must check how to set up tests without compile-time dependencies on XmlPath.\\n\\n**Analyzing compile errors**\\n\\nI’m considering possible causes for the compile errors. It doesn't seem related to the filename being uppercase. The `public class` instruction should generally work fine in Groovy, but maybe I can't have multiple public classes in one file. I'm also wondering if the compileTestGroovy fails due to existing files conflicting with `Xml_pathTest.groovy`. There might be a limitation with the native image test generator and how TCK handles multiple files. If existing tests remain unchanged, can I add new test classes without issues? I need to explore ways to resolve this.\\n\\n**Considering test modifications**\\n\\nI'm exploring how to get the tests to pass. One idea is to replace the current test with a \\\"plain\\\" JUnit test that has no external imports, but I still need to ensure I cover the uncovered feature. If compiling issues stem from the XmlPath import, that complicates things. Could I also try using fully qualified names for imports? What about removing the test file altogether? The user insists on maintaining tests, so maybe I should update existing placeholders instead, while adhering to their request for unchanged tests. I'm still unsure how harness limitations might impact this.\\n\\n**Investigating compile issues**\\n\\nI'm thinking there might be a compile failure happening due to the Native image plugin needing the test class name to be exactly `${artifact-id with underscores}Test`. Maybe there are additional tests that weren't included? While the overall compile is fine, I should look into the settings and see if Gradle convention is scanning only one class. Let’s inspect that further!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_02855ba501e27c0b0169ff591e950c81a38c42a69c8b3a1c44\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp_1kr6Q6zdXDyWz9sl7QZEEv8ijZI186uDMH-S2CII3YgoC8xN_boXN8pKeyL6ZYTf69cNkYy1kMX1UJLtOzn9QtGmkPRM1tWdMJc89xYcOWxKKJd3cqtieFRaprdq5n9Ay3vrcdBw0dh4nH-FlFr0Y8UtEfVikOgUoT0wirNP8js6IPQQijDp1V0tSPYY2uj51MINpaO16h9b8thyor2hOjWiYAog8W7rgsDLaXXIn8dF3LdB7tk_35J1q_2bRhgdVCGFwKobO5_948j6pmM78wo5WwjGsFT8g4BaXRYg5Ts8VYvP6_5buhEW143TsxAFfTAcmFIdqDSM3RBbRTIHGfmKQHKf_8o28VF7IuTWVAkY9n6vKs0TnjLC1QDDlICl-1rsKtZ5